Prep the veggies: Wash and dry all produce. Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. Core and slice the @Roma Tomato{2}(cores and sliced into wedges). Quarter the @Cucumber{2}(quartered lengthwise), then cut them into ½-inch pieces. Mince the @Garlic{4%cloves}(minced). Cut the @Demi-Baguette{2}(cut into 3/4-inch cubes). Pick the @Parsley{¼%oz}(leaves picked from stems) leaves from the stems, then discard the stems.

Marinate the tomatoes: In a #medium bowl{}, combine @Balsamic Vinegar{2%tablespoons} and @Olive Oil{2%tablespoons}. Toss in the tomatoes and season with @Salt{} and @Pepper{}.

Place the tomatoes on one side of a foil-lined #baking sheet{} and place in the oven for about ~{15%minutes}, until softened and slightly caramelized.

In a #shallow dish{}, coat the @Chicken Breasts{24%oz} with the @Pesto{4%oz}. Heat a drizzle of @Olive Oil{} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add the chicken to the pan and cook for ~{2-3%minutes} per side, until browned but not yet cooked through. Transfer to the #baking sheet{} in the oven to finish cooking for ~{5-10%minutes}, until cooked through. Remove the chicken from the oven to rest for ~{5%minutes}.

Make the croutons: Toss the baguette cubes on another baking sheet with the garlic, a drizzle of @Olive Oil{}, and a pinch of @Salt{} and @Pepper{}. Place in the oven to toast for about ~{10%minutes}, until golden brown and crispy on the outside.

Toss and Serve: Place the croutons in a #large bowl{} with the roasted tomatoes, cucumbers, and parsley leaves. Season generously with @Salt{} and @Pepper{}. Toss in the remaining @Balsamic Vinegar{2%tablespoons} and a large drizzle of @Olive Oil{}. Serve the roasted pesto chicken alongside and enjoy!

> Panzanella is a classic Tuscan dish best enjoyed in the warmer months. Created for the purpose of using up stale bread, it's a dish with humble roots. Together with fresh summer veggies and pesto chicken, we're transforming this modest dish to something worthy of company!